alse}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107338"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of increasing shortness of breath. He can now only walk to his mailbox before becoming breathless. He has heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (ejection fraction 32%) secondary to ischaemic cardiomyopathy. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes. His medications include furosemide, bisoprolol (at the maximum tolerated dose), spironolactone, sacubitril-valsartan, aspirin, metformin and empagliflozin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 82/min and regular, blood pressure 138/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 94% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. He has bilateral ankle oedema, an S3 gallop, and fine crackles throughout his lung fields. An electrocardiogram shows sinus rhythm. Recent investigations show haemoglobin 105 g/L (130-170), ferritin 25 \u03bcg/L (30-300), and transferrin saturation 12% (20-50%).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following should be added next to optimise heart failure management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carvedilol","Digoxin","Ivabradine","Verapamil","Nebivolol"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIvabradine\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next addition for this person with heart failure with reduced ejection fraction who remains symptomatic despite optimal pharmacological management. The key indication for ivabradine is a heart rate of 70 beats per minute or more in sinus rhythm despite maximally tolerated beta-blocker therapy. This patient has a heart rate of 82/min, which exceeds the threshold of 70/min, making him an ideal candidate. Ivabradine specifically lowers heart rate by inhibiting the I(f) current in the sinoatrial node, and has been shown to reduce hospitalisation and mortality in this setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDigoxin\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely recommended for people in sinus rhythm with heart failure with reduced ejection fraction. While it may provide symptomatic benefit in some cases, it does not reduce mortality and is generally reserved for those with atrial fibrillation or as a last-line therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarvedilol\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Enebivolol\u003C/strong\u003E, in addition to bisoprolol, is not appropriate, as combining two beta-blockers increases the risk of bradycardia and hypotension without additional benefit. Beta-blocker therapy should be optimised with a single agent at the maximum tolerated dose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVerapamil\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in heart failure with reduced ejection fraction due to its negative inotropic effects, which can worsen cardiac function and increase the risk of decompensation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is worth noting that this patient also has iron deficiency (ferritin 25 \u03bcg/L, transferrin saturation 12%), which is common in heart failure and associated with worse outcomes. After addressing the heart rate with ivabradine, consideration should be given to intravenous iron replacement, which has been shown to improve symptoms and reduce hospitalisations in people with heart failure and iron deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ivabradine is indicated in people with heart failure with reduced ejection fraction who remain symptomatic and have a heart rate of 70 beats per minute or more in sinus rhythm despite optimal pharmacological management, including maximally tolerated beta-blocker therapy.","Ivabradine is not effective in atrial fibrillation or when heart rate is controlled below 70 beats per minute.","Iron deficiency is common in heart failure and should be addressed with intravenous iron replacement to improve symptoms and reduce hospitalisations."],"references":["Heart Foundation of Australia and Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Guidelines for the Prevention, Detection, and Management of Heart Failure in Australia 2018: https://www.heartlungcirc.org/article/S1443-9506(18)31777-3/fulltextNational","Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF). In: eTG complete [Internet]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2023 Jun [cited 2025 Jun 1]. Available from: https://app.tg.org.au/etgcomplete"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89822"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11359"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89822"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-28T12:42:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-28T12:46:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4004"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107338"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https:/